<sect1 id="resources">
 <title>Further resources</title>
 <qandaset defaultlabel="qanda">
  <qandadiv>   
   <title>On your own machine</title>

   <qandaentry id="info-local"> 
    <question>
     <para>
       Where can I find information located on my machine?
     </para>
    </question>
    <answer>
     <para>
       Information is scattered all over the place. You can use the
       GNOME help browser (<command>gnome-help-browser</command> at
       the command line or select <menuchoice><guimenu>Programs</guimenu>
       <guimenuitem>Help system</guimenuitem></menuchoice> from the main
       GNOME menu) to browse most of these sources. A brief listing on a
       UNIX box would include the manual pages (<command>man gnome</command>),
       the info pages (<command>info gnome</command>), the documentation
       directory (usually <filename class="directory">/usr/doc/</filename>
       but it may be <filename class="directory">/usr/share/doc/</filename>
       on some systems) for packages, and the 
       <application>GNOME</application>-specific documentation for the
       GNOME help browser. You can also use your package management 
       tool as described earlier.
     </para>
    </answer>
   </qandaentry>
  </qandadiv>

  <qandadiv>
   <title>On the net</title>
   <qandaentry id="info-net"> 
    <question>
     <para>
       What about information on the net?
     </para>
    </question>
    <answer>
     <para>
       All over the place. A representative listing would include:
     </para>
     <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         The obvious place to start is the <ulink url="http://www.gnome.org"
         type="http">GNOME website</ulink>. Note that more detailed and
         technical information is at its sister site:
         <ulink type="http" url="http://developer.gnome.org">developer.gnome.org</ulink>.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         <ulink type="http" url="http://news.gnome.org/gnome-news/">Gnotices</ulink>
         is the website where much news is posted.
       </para> 
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         There are a variety of mailing lists for different purposes. A 
         reasonably complete mailing list page is at the <ulink type="http"
         url="http://www.gnome.org/resources/mailing-lists.html">main
         GNOME website</ulink>. Some lists are hosted elsewhere: 
         <application>Nautilus</application> discussion takes place on the
         <ulink type="http" 
         url="http://www.eazel.com/mailman/listinfo/nautilus-list">Nautilus
         list</ulink> hosted by 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.eazel.com">Eazel</ulink> and 
         a bunch of other lists are hosted at 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.helixcode.com">Helix Code</ulink>.
         <!-- I have lost the index for the mailman lists here. Help! -->
       </para>
       <note>
        <title>gnome-list and on-topicness</title>
        <para>
          The gnome-list mailing list in particular gets a lot of traffic,
          because people often aren't sure where to ask questions or simply
          don't know where to ask. It's really not the best place for
          X-related problems, distribution-related problems, questions on 
          how to mount a filesystem, perform backups, or what people's
          favourite mailers are.
        </para>
       </note>
       <para>
          For these and other non-GNOME questions, there are other mailing
          lists. Here's a partial list of where to look:
       </para>
       <itemizedlist>
        <listitem>
         <para>
           Red Hat users can head for the redhat-list found at the
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.redhat.com/mailing-lists/list_subscribe.html">Red
           Hat mailing lists</ulink> page on the
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.redhat.com">Red Hat</ulink>
           website.
         </para>
        </listitem>
        <listitem>
         <para>
           Debian users can head for several 
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.debian.org/MailingLists/">Debian
           mailing lists</ulink> on the
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.debian.org">Debian 
           website</ulink>.
         </para>
        </listitem>
        <listitem>
         <para>
            Mandrake users can head for several
            <ulink type="http" url="http://www.linux-mandrake.com/en/flists.php3">Mandrake
            mailing lists</ulink> on the
            <ulink type="http" url="http://www.linux-mandrake.com/en/">Mandrake
            website</ulink>.
         </para>
        </listitem>
        <listitem>
         <para>
           Caldera users can head for several
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.caldera.com/support/forums/">Caldera
           mailing lists</ulink> on the 
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.caldera.com">Caldera
           website</ulink>.
         </para>
        </listitem>
        <listitem>
         <para>
           Slackware doesn't have a specific "general questions" mailing list 
           listed in its
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.slackware.com/lists">mailing 
           lists</ulink> but there is apparently an active newsgroup which 
           handles a lot of newbie questions: alt.os.linux.slackware. 
         </para>
        </listitem>
        <listitem>
         <para>
           FreeBSD users can head for several
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.freebsd.org/handbook/eresources.html#ERESOURCES-MAIL">FreeBSD
           mailing lists</ulink> at the
           <ulink type="http" url="http://www.freebsd.org">FreeBSD website</ulink>.
           Note that few of these appear to have a charter involving questions
           from newbies. If one of those (or none) is the appropriate place,
           please let me know.
         </para>
        </listitem>
       </itemizedlist>
       <para>
         Further contributions welcomed.
       </para>
      </listitem>

      <listitem>
       <para>
         The Users Guide can be a source of useful information: you can
         always find the latest version in your local mirror of
         <ulink type="ftp" 
         url="ftp://ftp.gnome.org/pub/GNOME/stable/sources/users-guide/">
         ftp.gnome.org/pub/GNOME/stable/sources/users-guide/</ulink>. It
         is available to browse online at
         <ulink type="http"
         url="http://www.labs.redhat.com/gug/users-guide/">
         http://www.labs.redhat.com/gug/users-guide/</ulink>.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         People who want to dig deeper may want to look at the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://cvs.gnome.org">CVS browser</ulink>
         which lets you see who's done what recently and what's currently
         in there. This is where all the central code for GNOME lives.
       </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
       <para>
         Some applications are covered in more detail on other
         websites: the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.helixcode.com">Helix Code</ulink>, 
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.eazel.com">Eazel</ulink> and
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.labs.redhat.com/news.shtml">RHAD 
         Labs Rumor Mill</ulink>
         sites often have information; and many GNOME applications have
         homepages at the
         <ulink type="http" url="http://www.sourceforge.net">SourceForge</ulink>
         site: just search for the word <quote>gnome</quote> in the box.
       </para>
      </listitem>
     </itemizedlist>
    </answer>
   </qandaentry>
  </qandadiv>
 </qandaset>
</sect1>
